[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/jacoby_2nt_splinters"]
[Student "S"]
{When partner opens 1\S you have a pretty normal Jacoby 2NT response. He next says 3\S.  

Your partner has a better than minimum hand with 6 \Ss. However, you have an average hand with no controls to show so you use the Principle of Fast Arrival and bid 4\S. Everyone passes.}

[Event ""]
[Site ""]
[Date ""]
[Board "3"]
[Dealer "E"]
[Vulnerable "EW"]
[Deal "E:Q74.AQT83.87.KQ6 JT85.64.962.A842 AK3.KJ95.KQJ3.97 962.72.AT54.JT53"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "5H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1H pass 2NT pass 4H pass 4S pass 5H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "229237496ab0cf58840c7bd3ec148941295086cf70fc1e4a398b767d6b840d0e"]
[Category "Bidding Conventions"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/jacoby_2nt_splinters"]
[Student "S"]
{Partner's bid is game forcing. With a bare minimum, no singletons, you go ahead and sign off in game. Partner then says 4\S.  

Partner is definitely showing slam interest. If you had a first round control in either Minor suit you would bid it now. But you don't. So you sign of again, this time at 5\H. Partner finally gives up on the idea of slam and passes.}

